- subshell-exit-trap-output-misdirected: an EXIT (also DEBUG/RETURN)
  trap's own output always lands on the top-level shell's original
  stdout, never wherever the (sub)shell whose exit fired it had its
  own output going -- neither a plain "> file" redirect on the
  subshell nor capturing it via "$(...)" gets any of the trap's
  output. Confirmed via `od`/direct file checks, not just terminal
  display. The parent also doesn't wait for the trap to actually
  finish running before continuing on to its own next command, so the
  trap's (misdirected) output can appear interleaved arbitrarily late
  relative to whatever runs after the subshell. Most likely an
  eval-frame/fdstack teardown ordering issue: trap_exit()/trap_debug()/
  trap_return() run through the eval frame's destructor callback (see
  src/builtin/builtin_trap.c), and whatever fdstack state is current at
  that point appears to already be the *outer* one, not the
  (sub)shell's own. Not yet root-caused past that.

    X=$( ( trap 'echo trap-ran' EXIT; : ) )
    echo "captured=[$X]"
    # prints "captured=[]" then "trap-ran" on its own line -- should
    # print "captured=[trap-ran]" and nothing else

- kill-arg-redirect-parse: a redirection ("N>word"/"N<word") right
  after a command argument that's both (a) preceded somewhere earlier
  by a "-N"-shaped argument (a dash followed only by digits, e.g. a
  signal number given to the new `kill` builtin -- `kill -0 "$pid"`)
  and (b) itself quoted or the result of an expansion, is not
  recognized as a redirection at all -- it's handed to the command as
  a literal trailing argument instead. A literal (unquoted, unexpanded)
  word in that same position parses fine, so this isn't about
  redirection parsing in general, just this specific combination.
  Found via `kill -0 "$pid" 2>/dev/null` (kill sees "2>/dev/null" as a
  bogus extra operand); not yet isolated to the exact parser state
  involved.

    echo -0 "x" 2>/dev/null
    # prints "-0 x 2>/dev/null" -- should print "-0 x" (to stdout,
    # with fd 2 redirected to /dev/null)

    echo -0 x 2>/dev/null
    # prints "-0 x" correctly -- only the quoted/expanded case breaks

- sig-push-sigset-cast: sig_push() reinterprets sigset_t through an
  unsigned long*, UB on any ABI where sizeof(sigset_t) differs;
  currently harmless because the function is unused (dead code, not
  reachable from any shell script).

- sh-onsig-async-unsafe: sh_onsig(), the SIGCHLD handler, calls
  term_erase()/term_restore()/buffered i/o directly from signal-handler
  context; none of that is async-signal-safe. Any background job
  finishing exercises the handler, though the unsafety is a latent
  race, not a deterministic per-run failure.

    sleep 1 &
    sleep 2 &
    wait

- fnmatch-bracket-collating-range: a bracket-expression range whose
  endpoints are themselves "[.x.]"-wrapped collating symbols (as
  opposed to bare characters, e.g. "[0-2]") doesn't match as a range
  at all -- lib/path/path_fnmatch.c's range-detection only recognizes
  "X-Y" where X and Y are literal single characters, not
  "[.X.]-[.Y.]"; each "[.symbol.]" gets matched as its own standalone
  member (fixes/67 added support for that part on its own) and the
  "-" in between as a third, literal "-" member, rather than the three
  being fused into a single range. Found while confirming
  fnmatch-p-hang's fix didn't paper over anything else in the same
  test block; POSIX 2.13.1 does define this range form but it's a
  narrow, rarely-used corner of bracket-expression syntax.

    case 1 in [[.0.]-[.2.]]) echo matched;; *) echo no;; esac
    # prints "no"; POSIX says this range covers 0-2, so it should
    # print "matched"

- case-pattern-bracket-quote-stripping: a "case" pattern with a quoted
  substring inside a bracket expression (e.g. "[\".]"/'["."]', which
  ought to reduce to the bracket expression "[.]" after quote removal,
  matching a literal ".") matches nothing at all -- not just failing
  to match correctly, but every arm of the "case" including the "*"
  catch-all is silently skipped, as if the whole case-item's pattern
  list came out empty. This looks like a parser-level bug (the
  case-item's pattern node(s) apparently never get built at all for
  this shape) rather than a runtime fnmatch/glob-matching issue.
  Found via tests/posix/fnmatch-p.tst's "brackets and quotations" and
  "quotations of quotations" blocks, both of which fail on exactly
  this (not on the fnmatch-p-hang bug fixed alongside them, which
  those two blocks don't otherwise exercise).

    y="."
    case "$y" in
    ["."]) echo matched;;
    *) echo no;;
    esac
    # prints nothing at all -- neither "matched" nor "no"


